textDisplay: Hi Jenn, look forward to yr Paris vlog. Tfs yr packing tips so i thought I will share my travel tips too as I do travel few times a year & normally i will not unpack my toiletries & make up bag after travel as it is so convenient to just grab it & fly again. I stock my toner, moisturiser, toothpaste etc in mini size instead of full size in my toiletries bag & i only bring the travel size make up kit that has eyeshadows, blush, highlighter, contour, lip gloss all in one palette so it was light n easy to carry & i only bring one dual brush that does the whole job... i might throw in an extra eyeliner, lippy, super striking eyeshadow cake for any events so it was always light in my suitcase. As years goes by, i collected a lot of free mini sizes toner, cream etc when buying bulk cosmetics from the SA as i've always ask for sample or free gifts so it was very useful for travelling.. hope to share my experiencesüëãü•∞üéàüòò

textDisplay:
Lynn Ly oh it depends on what you have, obviously it you're close to dying you will pass quickly lol. it's a lot more complex than free healthcare=long waits but to sum it up, the emergency rooms are always completly packed here (especially in the winter), and there's more people than the emergencies capacity could allow to receive in a respectable timeframe. so the more serious your condition is, the quicker you will pass, and a cold is probably at the bottom of the list unless you're a baby or old (and even then lol). tbh the hospitals just really disencourage people to go there for colds and suggest instead you go see your regular doctor. that way it reduces the amount of people in emergency rooms and makes it quicker for people with more serious problems, bc if you're not very seriously ill it's normal to wait up to 24 hours to see a doctor at the hospital.

i hope this was clear hehe i'm not a native english speaker!

also it's probably different in each province, i am in quebec.
